  "final_analysis": "The treatment of peptic ulcer disease caused by chronic NSAID use involves addressing the underlying mechanisms of mucosal damage and acid secretion. Misoprostol, as a prostaglandin analog, directly counteracts the effect of NSAIDs on prostaglandin synthesis, which is crucial for maintaining gastric mucosal integrity and reducing acid secretion. This makes it particularly suitable for NSAID-induced ulcers. Esomeprazole, a proton pump inhibitor, effectively reduces gastric acid secretion, which aids in ulcer healing but does not specifically address the prostaglandin depletion caused by NSAIDs. Pirenzepine and Loratadine are less relevant in this context, with Pirenzepine being less effective in enhancing mucosal protection and Loratadine not being indicated for gastric acid-related issues at all. Based on the mechanism of action and the specific pathology induced by NSAIDs, Misoprostol is the most appropriate choice, aligning with medical consensus on its role in such cases.",
